@node "About" "WHAT IS THIS GAME ?"
This is a Video Poker game written specifically for the DLG BBS system.  It
doesn't work with other BBS software.  I've written a couple of online games
for DLG, and when I started programming, this was the game that was requested
the most (mostly by Richard Muller).  So, here it is.

I hate to say it, but because I spent SO much time writing this game, I'm
asking for a measly $10 shareware registration fee.  If you don't register the
game it's still completely playable.  BUT, only 5 people can play in each game,
and you can't view the top 5 Gamblers List.

Anyway, I hope you enjoy the game.  I'm almost finished with a Keno game
(requested by Rich McBride), and so you'll probably see that game on AmiNet
soon too!  One thing I highly recommend - install the GamesInfo program on
your BBS.  It will attract a LOT more players to Video Poker.
@endnode

@node "Install" "INSTALLATION"
Here we go again - Installation.  :)

The game is pretty easy to install.  First, copy the VPoker file to wherever
you'd like.  Second, create a directory called GameData somewhere.  Then
assign GameData: to this directory.  If you've already installed one of my
other games (10,000 or Card Sharks), you can skip step two...

Now, create a menu item from the DLG Configurations menu - it should look like
the following:

[ 1] Letter:                   K
[ 2] Executable: (path/name)   Doors:VPoker/VPoker %PORT 20 50 9600
[ 4] Description:              Video Poker
[ 5] Type:                     Executable
[ 6] Help File:                doors/K
[ 7] Lower level:              5
[ 8] Upper level:              255
[ 9] Hidden:                   NO
[10] Load type:                OVERLAY
[11] Ask user if sure:         NO
[12] Pend messages:            YES
[13] Cli mode:                 NO
[14] Pause on completion:      NO
[15] Log value:                190
[16] Activity string:
[17] Priority:                 DEFAULT
[18] Edit help file

If you just execute VPoker, it will give you information about the command
line stuff.  But if you don't want to have to do that, here's a quick
explanation:

%PORT is a DLG Switch that MUST be included or the game won't know who's
      playing or any other information about the user.

20    This is the number of turns per day.  20 is recommended, although you
      can make it anything you want!

50    This is the normal MAXIMUM bet that a user can make.  Again, 50 is
      recommended, but it's up to you.

9600  This is the MINIMUM baud rate required to play the game.  The reason
      this is here is because there's quite a bit of screen movement, and
      for slower callers, it could take them quite a while to play.  Plus
it's
      not very fun when the screen redraw is slow.  9600 is recommended.

That's all there is to it, if you have any questions, let me know!

I also recommend you install the @{"GamesInfo" link "GameInfo" 0} program for use with this game!
@endnode

@node "Registering" "REGISTRATION"
This game is Shareware, and if you'd like to register, send $10 to me with the
following information.  You can then get the key file in a couple of different
ways - see below.

                          Your Name:
                      Your BBS Name:
             Your DLG Serial Number:
 (two letters followed by 4 digits)
              Your BBS Phone Number:
    Where you obtained this program:
 How you'd like to get your keyfile:

Keyfile options:

1. You can log onto @{"The Fly By Night" link "FBN" 0}, and I can leave it
   there for you.

2. I can UUEncode the keyfile and send it to you through Internet E-Mail.
   (This is fastest & cheapest)

3. You can send me $10 with a blank disk return postage and I'll mail it to
   you. (This is the SLOWEST and most expensive)


Just for the fun of it, my Christmas gift this year to everyone is:

If your registration money/info is postmarked by December 31, 1994, you can
register for only $5 instead of $10.

Send the above information/money to me at: Steve Herring
                                           12617 SE Boise
                                           Portland, OR 97236
@endnode

